<Window xmlns="https://github.com/avaloniaui"
        xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
        x:Class="ZyncMaster.App.Windows.MainWindow"
        Title="Zync Master"
        Icon="/Assets/icon.png"
        Width="440" Height="680"
        MinWidth="380" MinHeight="560"
        ExtendClientAreaToDecorationsHint="True"
        ExtendClientAreaChromeHints="NoChrome"
        ExtendClientAreaTitleBarHeightHint="-1"
        Background="#0c0e16"
        TransparencyLevelHint="None"
        CanResize="True"
        ShowInTaskbar="True"
        WindowStartupLocation="CenterScreen">
  <!-- Frameless-but-resizable chrome. ACTIVE = Option A (extend client area, no chrome).

       GOAL: visually frameless (no top strip) + native resize on the 4 edges/corners +
       working maximize/restore with no WebView2 "snow".

       === Option A (ACTIVE) — ExtendClientArea*, NoChrome ===
         ExtendClientAreaToDecorationsHint="True"  -> the client area is drawn over the
           whole decoration area, so the window manager paints NO top strip/border on top
           of our content. This is what removes the ugly top border the user marked.
         ExtendClientAreaChromeHints="NoChrome"     -> no OS caption buttons / title bar.
         ExtendClientAreaTitleBarHeightHint="-1"    -> let the platform pick the (collapsed)
           caption height; our content covers it. The window manager STILL owns the resize
           hit-test on all 4 edges/corners (extend-to-decorations keeps the WM frame for
           resizing — it just isn't painted), so dragging an edge resizes instead of falling
           through to the WebView2 child HWND (the airspace bug stays fixed).

         Why this is now safe even though it was removed before: the earlier desync was
         ExtendClientArea* WITHOUT a re-layout on WindowState changes — maximize/restore left
         the WebView2's CoreWebView2 bounds at the previous state ("lost everything" on
         restore). That re-layout handler now EXISTS in MainWindow.axaml.cs (PropertyChanged on
         WindowStateProperty -> InvalidateHostLayout), so the host re-measures/-arranges on
         every state change and the WebView2 bounds follow the new client size. Transparency
         stays OFF (TransparencyLevelHint="None") + opaque Background, which is what killed the
         maximize "snow"; Option A does not touch that, so the snow fix is preserved.

       === Option B (FALLBACK) — revert to the previous BorderOnly chrome ===
         If Option A reintroduces ANY WebView2 desync on maximize/restore, revert these three
         attributes to a single line:  WindowDecorations="BorderOnly"
         That restores the known-good resize+maximize behaviour at the cost of the thin top
         strip the user dislikes. It is a one-line swap with no other code change required.

       RISK NOTE (UI could not be run here): Option A is expected to remove the top strip and
       keep resize+maximize working given the re-layout handler is already in place, but this
       was NOT verified live. If maximize/restore regresses, switch to Option B above.

       The embedded WebView2 (or the loopback placeholder) fills the client area; the
       web UI hides its own cosmetic title bar's OS-chrome when it detects the shell. -->
  <Panel x:Name="HostPanel">
    <StackPanel HorizontalAlignment="Center" VerticalAlignment="Center" Spacing="12">
      <TextBlock Text="Zync Master"
                 Foreground="White"
                 FontSize="24"
                 FontWeight="SemiBold"
                 HorizontalAlignment="Center" />
      <TextBlock x:Name="HostUrlText"
                 Text="Starting web panel…"
                 Foreground="#9FB0CC"
                 FontSize="13"
                 HorizontalAlignment="Center"
                 TextAlignment="Center"
                 TextWrapping="Wrap"
                 MaxWidth="340" />
      <Button x:Name="OpenPanelButton"
              Content="Open web panel"
              HorizontalAlignment="Center" />
    </StackPanel>
  </Panel>
</Window>
